(2458, NULL, 'Iran is the 18th largest country in the world, with a total of 1,648,195 sq km. It is slightly smaller than Alaska.', '2012-11-23 17:34:58'),
(2459, NULL, 'The Iranian population in 2012 was 78,868,711, making it the 18th most populated country in the world.', '2012-11-23 17:34:58'),
(2460, NULL, 'A December 2003 earthquake struck the southeastern city of Bam, Iran, killing more than 30,000 people.', '2012-11-23 17:34:58'),
(2461, NULL, 'The name Italy comes from the word italia, meaning “calf land,” perhaps because the bull was a symbol of the Southern Italian tribes.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2462, NULL, 'Italy is approximately 116,400 square miles (including Sicily and Sardinia), which is slightly larger than Arizona.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2463, NULL, 'The official name of Italy is the Italian Republic (Repubblica Italiana).', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2464, NULL, 'Italy is said to have more masterpieces per square mile than any other country in the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2465, NULL, 'Almost four-fifths of Italy is either mountainous or hilly.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2466, NULL, 'The Italian wolf is Italy’s unofficial national animal and plays a large role in the legend of the founding of Rome.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2467, NULL, 'The author of “Pinocchio” (“pine nut”), Carlo Collodi (1826-1890), was Italian.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2468, NULL, 'There are two independent states within Italy: the Republic of San Marino (25 square miles) and the Vatican City (just 108.7 acres).', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2469, NULL, 'The highest peak in Europe is in Italy. Monte Bianco (White Mountain) is 15,771 feet high and is part of the Alps.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2470, NULL, 'In northern Italy, last names tend to end in “i”, while those from the south often end in “o.” The most common Italian surname is Russo.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2471, NULL, 'Over 50 million tourists a year visit Italy. Tourism is vital to Italy’s economy and provides nearly 63% of Italy’s national income.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2472, NULL, 'When European Jews were being persecuted during WWII, it was not unusual for some Jews to hide in Italy’s ancient catacombs.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2473, NULL, 'Approximately 85% of Italians are Roman Catholics, with Protestants, Jews, and a growing Muslim community making up the minority.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2474, NULL, 'The world’s longest land tunnel is the Lötschberg Base Tunnel, which proves a 22-mile railway link between Switzerland and Italy.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2475, NULL, 'Italy was one of the founders of the EU and is a member of the Group of Eight (G8), a forum for eight of the world’s most powerful nations.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2476, NULL, 'A part of northern Italy called Val Camonica contains about 350,000 petroglyphs that were created nearly 10,000 years ago.', '2012-11-23 17:35:01'),
(2477, NULL, 'The official name of Mexico is Estados Únidos Mexicanos (United Mexican States).', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2478, NULL, 'A Mexican tamale called the zacahuil is three feet long and weighs about 150 pounds.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2479, NULL, 'Mexico introduced chocolate, corn, and chilies to the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2480, NULL, 'Mexico is home to a very rare rabbit called the volcano rabbit which lives near Mexican volcanoes.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2481, NULL, 'The largest wildcat in North America is the jaguar, which can be found in Mexico''s southern jungles.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2482, NULL, 'The first printing press in North America was used in Mexico City in 1539.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2483, NULL, 'The National University of Mexico was founded in 1551 by Charles V of Spain and is the oldest university in North America.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2484, NULL, 'The border between Mexico and the United States is the second largest border in the world (only the U.S.-Canadian border is longer).', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2485, NULL, 'Mexico is second only to Brazil in the number of Catholic citizens.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2486, NULL, 'Mexico is located in the “Ring of Fire,” one of the earth’s most violent earthquake and volcano zones.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2487, NULL, 'The Chihuahua is the world’s smallest dog and is named for a Mexican state.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2488, NULL, 'Mexico’s size is 756,066 square miles, which is almost three times larger than Texas.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2489, NULL, 'Only ten countries in the world have a larger population than Mexico’s 109,955,400 million people.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2490, NULL, 'Mexico City has the highest elevation and is oldest city in North America. It is also one of the largest cities in the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2491, NULL, 'Mexico is the 14th largest country in the world by total area.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2492, NULL, 'One unusual Mayan weapon was a “hornet bomb,” which was an actual hornet’s nest thrown at enemies during battle.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2493, NULL, 'The Aztecs played ritual ball game known as tlachtli in which the losers were often sacrificed to the gods.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2494, NULL, 'While bullfighting is Mexico''s national sport, fútbol (soccer in the U.S.) is currently more popular.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2495, NULL, 'Texas was a Mexican province which declared its independence from Mexico in 1836, resulting in war with the United States (1836-1838).', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2496, NULL, 'Actor Anthony Quinn was the first Mexican to win an Academy Award for his role in the 1952 movies Viva Zapata.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2497, NULL, 'The Chichen Itza Pyramid in Mexico was named one of the new Seven Wonders of the World.', '2012-11-23 17:35:02'),
(2498, NULL, 'Though smaller in size, South Korea has a population more than double that of North Korea.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2499, NULL, 'The word Korea, which many believe Marco Polo took with him to Europe, means “land of high mountains and sparkling streams.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2500, NULL, 'The North Korean government strictly controls all levels of education. The literacy rate of those aged 15 and older in North Korea is 99%.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2501, NULL, 'Kim Jong-il is only 5'' 2'''' tall. He wears four-inch lifts in his shoes to compensate for his short stature.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2502, NULL, 'Kim Jong-il has a collection of over 20,000 movies, including all the James Bond films.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2503, NULL, 'The average life expectancy of North Koreans is 61 years for males and 66 years for females.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2504, NULL, 'North Korea houses the world’s largest flagpole, at 525'' high. The flag it holds weighs approximately 600 pounds.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2505, NULL, 'North Korea has three Internet hosts. The United States has the most in the world, with 439 million.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2506, NULL, 'In contrast to South Korea’s per capita GDP of $18,000, North Korea’s GDP is $1,000.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2507, NULL, 'Unlike in the U.S., where people sit on seesaws, both North and South Koreans stand while playing the game.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2508, NULL, 'Kim Il-sung Square in the Pyongyang (“capital of willows”) capital is larger than Red Square in Moscow.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2509, NULL, 'The DMZ (demilitarized zone) along the 38th parallel is the most heavily guarded border in the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2510, NULL, 'Newlyweds in North Korea swear loyalty to both Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-il. They place a gift at the feet of a statue of Kim Il-sung.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2511, NULL, 'North Korea’s main employers are the government and the military.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2512, NULL, 'North Korean families have an average of two children.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2513, NULL, 'North Korea is the last Stalinist state on Earth.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2514, NULL, 'North Korea was accepted into the United Nations in 1991.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2515, NULL, 'After his death, Kim Il-sung was declared the country’s “Eternal President.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2516, NULL, 'In large North Korean cities, women are not allowed to wear pants or ride bicycles. Women’s skirts must cover their knees.', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2517, NULL, 'North Korea is ranked second to last on the World Press Freedom Index. (Eritrea is last.)', '2012-11-23 17:35:04'),
(2518, NULL, 'The quill pen is thought to have originated in Spain about 1,400 years ago.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2519, NULL, 'The official name of Spain is the Kingdom of Spain.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2520, NULL, 'Spanish explorer Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo (1499-1543) discovered California.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2521, NULL, 'In 1603, Spanish sailor Gabriel de Castilla (1577-1620) became the first the man ever to see Antarctica.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2522, NULL, 'Spanish sailor Juan Sebasti�n Elcano (1476-1526) was the first man to circumnavigate the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2523, NULL, 'Spanish explorer Vasco N��ez de Balboa (1475-1519) was the first European to see the Pacific Ocean.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2524, NULL, 'The Phoenicians who entered Spain in the 8th century B.C. called the peninsula Span or “the hidden land.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2525, NULL, 'The official language of Spain is Castilian Spanish (74%), though Catalan (17%) Galician (7%), and Basque (2%) are also spoken.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2526, NULL, 'Spanish inventor Manuel Jal�n Corominas (1925-2011) invented the mop in 1956.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2527, NULL, 'Spanish sailor and engineer Isaac Peral (1851-1895) designed the first fully operative military submarine.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2528, NULL, 'Spanish surgeon and scientist Miguel Servet (1511-1553) was the first European to describe pulmonary circulation.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2529, NULL, 'Spain is home to a type of tailless monkey, the macaque, which is the only type of wild monkey that lives in Europe.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2530, NULL, 'Spain and Portugal provide most of the world’s cork. Cork trees flourish in the dry Meseta region in Spain.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2531, NULL, 'Spain is the second largest country in Western Europe after France and the second most mountainous after Switzerland.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2532, NULL, 'The largest producer of olive oil, Spain accounts for 45% of the world’s total olive oil production.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2533, NULL, 'The ancient Roman Aqueduct of Segovia in Spain was built in the 1st century A.D. and still supplies water to the city.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2534, NULL, 'The estimated annual cost of desertification in Spain due to climate change and pool land use is $200 million.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2535, NULL, 'Muslims founded the first Spanish university at Valencia in 1209.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2536, NULL, 'Enrollment at Spain’s universities more than doubled from 692,000 in 1982 to 1,540,596 in 2001.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2537, NULL, 'When a child loses a tooth in Spain, a small mouse called “Ratoncito P�rez” leaves a surprise under the pillow.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2538, NULL, 'Spain legalized same sex marriage in 2005.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2539, NULL, 'There are no laws against public nudity in Spain.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2540, NULL, 'Spain has the lowest age of consent for sexual activity in Europe at 13 years old. Both Malta and Turkey have the highest at 18.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2541, NULL, 'Tipping is not common in Spain, especially for cheap dinners.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2542, NULL, 'Spain’s national sport is fútbol, or soccer.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2543, NULL, 'The name “Madrid” is from the Arabic magerit, which means “place of many streams.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2544, NULL, 'Spain has some of the largest gold deposits in Europe. It is also one of the world biggest producers of granite and marble.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2545, NULL, 'The Rio Tinto River in Spain is so polluted by toxic pollution from 5,000 years of mining that it contains little to no life.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2546, NULL, 'Spain is the least densely populated country in Europe, with just 202 inhabitants per square mile.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2547, NULL, 'In 1993, just 1.7% of student enrollment for technical institutes and colleges were women. In 2000, it was up to 40%.', '2012-11-23 17:35:05'),
(2548, NULL, 'The world’s smallest mammal, the Craseonycteris thonglongyai (the bumble bat), is found in Thailand.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2549, NULL, 'Thailand houses the world’s largest fish, the 12-meter Rhincodon typus, otherwise known as the whale shark.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2550, NULL, 'Medicine man Hoo Sateow from Thailand has the world’s documented longest hair at 16'' 11" long. He says his hair “keeps him nice and warm.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2551, NULL, 'Thailand is the world’s 51st largest country. Russia is the largest. The United States is third largest.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2552, NULL, 'Thailand is slightly larger than the size of Wyoming at 198,115 square miles (513,115 sq km).', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2553, NULL, 'Seventy five percent of the people in Thailand are Thai, 14% are Chinese, and 11% are “other.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2554, NULL, 'Thailand is home to the world’s hairiest child, Supatra “Nat” Sasuphan.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2555, NULL, 'A nuclear family in Thailand is rare because most people live in large extended families.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2556, NULL, 'One-tenth of all animal species on Earth live in Thailand.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2557, NULL, 'More than 1,500 species of orchids grow wild in Thai forests. Thailand is the world’s number one orchid exporter.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2558, NULL, 'The largest living lizard is native to Thailand. The monitor lizard can grow as long as 7 feet.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2559, NULL, 'Approximately 10% of the world’s bird species live in Thailand, a greater proportion than in all of Europe or North America.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2560, NULL, 'World-famous golfer Tiger Woods is the son of an American father and a Thai mother.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2561, NULL, 'Just as the bald eagle is a symbol of the U.S., the Garuda (a creature from the Hindu religion) is a national and royal symbol of Thailand.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2562, NULL, 'One in 10 Thais live in Bangkok, the nation’s capital and largest city.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2563, NULL, 'Bangkok is one of Asia’s top tourist destinations. In 2005, more than 11 million foreign tourists visited in the city.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2564, NULL, 'Thailand is the world’s largest producer of tin.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2565, NULL, 'Each year, around six million foreign tourists visit Thailand. Thailand has also attracted many expatriates from developed countries.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2566, NULL, 'President Andrew Jackson initiated the first official contact with Thailand in the 19th century.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2567, NULL, 'The first case of HIV/Aids was reported in Thailand in 1984. Thailand currently has the highest prevalence of HIV in Asia.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2568, NULL, 'Thailand has one of the worst child sex trafficking records in the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:07'),
(2569, NULL, 'Rome has a sovereign state located entirely in its city limits, the Vatican City, which is also the world’s smallest state.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2570, NULL, 'The snake was a common image in Roman art and jewelry and was believed to have powers over a family’s well-being.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2571, NULL, 'Sometimes gladiator blood was recommended by Roman physicians as an aid to fertility.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2572, NULL, 'After the death of an emperor, an eagle (symbol of the god Jupiter) was released to bear his soul to heaven.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2573, NULL, 'In response to a 73 B.C. revolt against Rome by Spartacus the gladiator, 6,000 slaves were crucified.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2574, NULL, 'The Romans were the first civilization to use concrete and the arch with any notable skill.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2575, NULL, 'Rome’s first university, La Sapienza (est. A.D. 1303), is the largest in Europe and the second largest in the world.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2576, NULL, 'The word “palace” comes from the Palatine Hill, where Augustus established the emperors’ tradition of building their palaces.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2577, NULL, 'A man could lose Roman citizenship if he deserted the army, mutilated himself so he could not serve, or dodged a census to evade taxation.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2578, NULL, 'Romans thought that not owning slaves was a sign of extreme poverty. Many people would take three slaves with them just to go to the baths.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2579, NULL, 'The Romans trained some female slaves to fight as gladiators.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2580, NULL, 'For the Romans, a “circus” was a chariot racetrack, not the tented entertainment venue of today.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2581, NULL, 'In battle, Romans sometimes grouped together and held their shields all around them in a move called “the tortoise.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2582, NULL, 'Roman days were divided into 12 hours, measured by a sundial.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2583, NULL, 'Roman coins were used to publicize the emperor, his achievements, and his family in a world with no mass media.', '2012-11-23 17:35:12'),
(2584, NULL, 'The Romans had gods for doors (Forculus), hinges (Cardea), and thresholds (Limentinus).', '2012-11-23 17:35:12');
INSERT INTO `factoid` (`id`, `source`, `description`, `created`) VALUES
(2585, NULL, 'The word Hawaii is from the Proto-Polynesian hawaiki, meaning “place of the gods” or “homeland.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2586, NULL, 'Born in Hawaii, Barack Obama is the only president from outside the continental United States.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2587, NULL, 'Because of its continuous volcanic eruptions, Hawaii is the only state in the nation to have an increasing land area.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2588, NULL, 'Hawaii has two official languages, Hawaiian and English, though Pidgin, Samoan, and Tongan are also spoken.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2589, NULL, 'Hawaii is the only state in the nation that grows coffee, has tropical rainforests, and is made completely of islands.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2590, NULL, 'In the 1960s, astronauts trained for moon voyages by walking on Mauna Loa’s hardened lava fields, which resemble the surface of the moon.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2591, NULL, 'Only two types of mammals are native to Hawaii: the hoary bat and the monk seal.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2592, NULL, 'When written with the English alphabet, Hawaiian uses only 12 letters and a symbol (‘).', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2593, NULL, 'Hawaii is America’s youngest state, entering the nation on August 21, 1959.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2594, NULL, 'The hula was originally a form of worship performed by highly trained men who were supposedly taught the dance by the Hawaiian god Luka.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2595, NULL, 'Ancient Hawaiians believed that the heavier a woman, especially a chieftess, the more beautiful she was.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2596, NULL, 'There are just over 7,000 inhabitants on the island of Molokai, probably most famous for its past as a leper colony.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2597, NULL, 'The southernmost state in the United States is Hawaii.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2598, NULL, 'The rainiest place on Earth is Mt. Waialeale on the island of Kauai, where the average rainfall is 476 inches per year.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2599, NULL, 'Hawaiians considered the shark (mano) a god and treated it with great respect.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2600, NULL, 'The highest sea cliffs in the world are on Moloka’i.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2601, NULL, 'Hawaii has its own time zone and does not observe Daylight Saving Time.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2602, NULL, 'Oahu draws more visitors than any other island of Hawaii.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2603, NULL, 'The popular T.V. series Lost is shot in Hawaii. At the end of the credits is a note thanking the “people of Hawaii and their Aloha Spirit.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2604, NULL, 'The oldest Catholic Cathedral in the United States is the Cathedral of Our Lady of Peace in Honolulu, built in 1843.', '2012-11-23 17:35:13'),
(2605, NULL, 'The term “maverick” is derived from the name Samuel A. Maverick (1803-1870), an early Texas lawyer and pioneer.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2606, NULL, 'The bowie knife is named after the Alamo hero Jim Bowie (1796-1836). His brother, Rezin, designed the hefty weapon.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2607, NULL, 'The city of Slaughter, Texas, has never had a homicide.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2608, NULL, 'The largest city in Texas is Houston. It is also the fourth largest city in the United States.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2609, NULL, 'The deadliest natural disaster in the U.S. was the Galveston hurricane of 1900, which killed between 8,000-12,000 people.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2610, NULL, 'In 1969, Apollo 11 commander Neil Armstrong called Houston, Texas, from the moon. The first word spoken on the moon in 1969 was “Houston.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2611, NULL, 'The “father” of Texas is Stephen Fuller Austin (1793-1836). He and his father helped move 300 American families (“The Old 300”) to Texas.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2612, NULL, 'Each year Amarillo hosts the World’s Largest Calf Fry Cook-Off. “Calf fries” are bull testicles.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2613, NULL, 'Approximately 90% of the world’s recoverable helium is located in the ground under Amarillo, Texas.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2614, NULL, 'A $60 million treasure of gold plundered by Coronado is believed to be buried on an 80-acre pasture at the Sems Ranch near Clyde, Texas.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2615, NULL, 'The Dallas State Fair Park is home to the largest Ferris wheel (the Texas Star) in the Western Hemisphere.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2616, NULL, 'After the popularity of the song “Luckenbach, Texas,” so many road signs were stolen that the government stopped making them.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2617, NULL, 'Davy Crockett, who died at the Alamo, once told his Tennessee peers in Congress “Ya’ll can go to hell. I am going to Texas.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2618, NULL, 'Miriam A. “Ma” Ferguson was the first female governor of Texas and the first woman elected governor of any state.', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2619, NULL, 'Emily Morgan, an African American indentured servant, is the subject of the song “The Yellow Rose of Texas.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:14'),
(2620, NULL, 'In the Star Trek episode “Wolf in the Fold,” Spock foils the evil computer by commanding it to “compute to last digit the value of pi.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2621, NULL, 'Comedian John Evans once quipped: “What do you get if you divide the circumference of a jack-o''-lantern by its diameter? Pumpkin π.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2622, NULL, 'The symbol for pi (π) has been used regularly in its mathematical sense only for the past 250 years.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2623, NULL, 'A Givenchy men’s cologne named Pi is marketed as highlighting the sexual appeal of intelligent and visionary men.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2624, NULL, 'In the Greek alphabet, π (piwas) is the sixteenth letter. In the English alphabet, p is also the sixteenth letter.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2625, NULL, 'The first 144 digits of pi add up to 666 (which many scholars say is “the mark of the Beast”). And 144 = (6+6) x (6+6).', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2626, NULL, 'A mysterious 2008 crop circle in Britain shows a coded image representing the first 10 digits of pi.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2627, NULL, 'Pi is the secret code in Alfred Hitchcock’s Torn Curtain and in The Net starring Sandra Bullock.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2628, NULL, 'Computing pi is a stress test for a computer—a kind of “digital cardiogram.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2629, NULL, 'Umberto Eco’s famed book Foucault’s Pendulum associates the mysterious pendulum in the novel with the intrigue of pi.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2630, NULL, 'William Jones (1675-1749) introduced the symbol “π” in the 1706, and it was later popularized by Leonhard Euler (1707-1783) in 1737.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2631, NULL, 'Leonardo da Vinci (1452-1519) and artist Albrecht Durer (1471-1528) both briefly worked on “squaring the circle,” or approximating pi.', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
(2632, NULL, 'Pi is also referred to as the “circular constant,” “Archimedes’ constant,” or “Ludolph’s number.”', '2012-11-23 17:35:16'),
